Jaipur from one of the many forts high above the city, followed by a glimpse into the dense bustling streets below. 
@chelseakauai and I visited India in 2019 and fell in love with the vibrant culture and unique experiences found only in this wild country.

posts.desc: A misty sunrise in Cappadocia. The first pic was with an 800mm lens from the top of Love Valley.

Very few places really compare to India. Depending on the time of day or what doorway you walk through it‚Äôs peace and chaos, holy and mundane, ancient and modern all nearly tumbling on top of another. 

This was the most serene morning overlooking Udaipur and eating croissants beside the river. Emmett and I loved to go out every sunrise when everything was just waking up. Udaipur also was the only place we met up with local friends and that always changes a place for me. Makes it way better and feels more known through their eyes.

We would love to go back and check out more nature focused areas next time if you have any suggestions :)
-
Emmett also made a vlog of our time there if you haven‚Äôt watched it, it‚Äôs on his YouTube

We got to this stunning beach just after sunset and the sky turned a strange colour of purple while the clouds were lit up yellow. 
It took a while to get here, but it was worth the travel time. Remote places like this are filled with so many hidden gems.

posts.desc:
Sunrise at one of the most stunning beaches I‚Äôve ever seen. There was one man living on the beach (last photo) with untouched sand, and a giant reef.
We sat and chatted with him. He is 80 years old and has been living on this beach since 1970 in a small wooden shack. He spends his time painting in the incredible scenery surrounding his home. When we asked him why, he simple said ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt get along with society‚Äù.

posts.desc:
Have you ever had one of those days after a hike where you‚Äôre covered in dried sweat and dirt, your legs and feet are sore but you keep hiking, dehydrated and hungry, and yet you‚Äôre surrounded by awesome friends who have never complained about any of it? This was one of those days. 

It‚Äôs that feeling of being grubby and sore that becomes associated with the most rewarding views. It‚Äôs a strange parallel that makes you enjoy discomfort. It‚Äôs a sign that you‚Äôve physically pushed yourself and Mother Nature has gifted you with a show. 

We hiked to this viewpoint on Ua Pou and watched one of the most spectacular sunsets I‚Äôve ever seen. We hiked back under a sky full of stars, with cameras full of photos. 

Adventuring with @tahititourismenorthamerica @aranuicruises @airtahitinui @tahititourisme

posts.desc:
The weather on tropical islands changes rapidly. I find that there‚Äôs no point in checking a weather forecast because it‚Äôs so unpredictable most of the time. This unpredictability leads to dramatic clouds, rainstorms, perfect light and if you‚Äôre lucky, rainbows. 
I shot this on Ua Pou while we waited for sunset a few nights ago.
